 emotional. It indicates a taste for the natural and the "picturesque", foreshadowing romanticism. This first modern edition of the text is accompanied by an introduction and full commentary, covering both general considerations and specific points and topics. Contemporary illustrations have been chosen to illuminate further the gardens and places discussed. Michael Symes is an author, lecturer and garden historian. He founded the MA in Garden History at Birkbeck, University of London, and specialises in eighteenth-century gardens in Britain and on the continent.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aGardens, EnglishvEarly works to 1800. 0aLandscape architecturezEnglandvEarly works to 1800. 4aArchaeology & Heritage. 4aArt & Architecture. 4aEighteenth Century Studies. 7aGARDENING / Reference.2bisacsh  aEnglish culture.  aEnglish garden.  aEnglish high society.  aEnglish royal family.  aarchitecture.  aart.  aenvironment.  agarden historian.  agardening.  alandscaping.  anature.  aromanticism.1 aWhatel, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311143131440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178204626440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782046264423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782046264/original  a978-3-11-143131-4  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles